	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-otto bypostauthor even depth-2" id="comment-12089" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-12089" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0994d5e2e158a24ba8017c2525d78263?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name"><a itemprop='url' href='http://ottodestruct.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Otto</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2013/language-packs-101-prepwork/comment-page-1/#comment-12089">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2013-10-26T11:33:04+00:00">October 26, 2013 at 11:33 am</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>You still need to reference where the language files are in the load_*_textdomain call, if you&#8217;re including them yourself.</p>
<p>Theme developers will not change their translation file names at all. If you include your own pomo&#8217;s, then they remain just locale.mo. The language pack system will name them slug-locale.mo, but you won&#8217;t call them that or include them in the theme. The system will send them separately.</p>
<p>Finally, if you leave off the directory in the load_* call, then you won&#8217;t be able to include your own pomo files, it will just use the language packs if and when they exist.</p>
<p>This will become more clear as the structure gets built. For now, just ensure that you have the headers, that your text-domain is the slug, and that you&#8217;re calling the load_* function properly. Everything else will become clear over time.</p>
</div>

	<div class="reply">
	<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2013/language-packs-101-prepwork/?replytocom=12089#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-12089", "12089", "respond", "942")'>Reply to this comment</a>	</div>
